1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,360
In 1905, a 26-year-old patent clerk, a guy whose academic career had completely stalled,

2
00:00:06,360 --> 00:00:11,760
sat down between stamping other people's paperwork and casually rewrote the universe.

3
00:00:11,760 --> 00:00:20,560
Atoms, light, space and time itself, one man, one year, in his spare time.

4
00:00:20,560 --> 00:00:24,400
And here's the strange part, it feels like nobody does that anymore.

5
00:00:24,400 --> 00:00:29,680
Try to name a living Einstein, working today, and most of us like Stan here,

6
00:00:29,680 --> 00:00:35,760
just come up blank. So, what happened? Did humanity peak and start coasting?

7
00:00:35,760 --> 00:00:39,920
The real answer is a lot weirder, and it is not the one you are bracing for.

8
00:00:39,920 --> 00:00:44,080
And up close, what he actually pulled off in that one year is even more absurd.

9
00:00:44,080 --> 00:00:49,280
He proved that atoms are real, something scientists had argued about for centuries.

10
00:00:49,280 --> 00:00:55,840
He explained that light comes in tiny particles, the idea that would later win him the Nobel Prize.

11
00:00:55,840 --> 00:01:02,240
And then, almost as a side project, he rewrote space and time themselves with special relativity,

12
00:01:02,240 --> 00:01:07,360
and dropped in a little equation you have definitely heard of.

13
00:01:07,360 --> 00:01:13,600
E equals MC squared. Remember, his doctoral thesis had just been rejected.

14
00:01:13,600 --> 00:01:17,040
He was a nobody doing this between stamping patents.

15
00:01:17,040 --> 00:01:20,960
One man, one year, off the side of his desk.

16
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:24,480
And before you file that under abstract old-timey science,

17
00:01:24,480 --> 00:01:27,520
understand that it is running your life right now.

18
00:01:27,520 --> 00:01:30,800
The GPS in your pocket depends on his relativity.

19
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:33,520
Without the correction Einstein's math provides,

20
00:01:33,520 --> 00:01:37,680
your phone's location would drift off by about two kilometers every single day.

21
00:01:38,560 --> 00:01:44,080
The blue dot that finds you on a map exists because a bored patent clerk got curious about light.

22
00:01:44,960 --> 00:01:50,320
So, yes. Where are the Einsteins is a completely fair thing to ask.

23
00:01:51,120 --> 00:01:53,840
But here's the first crack in the question.

24
00:01:53,840 --> 00:01:56,960
The image in your head, the lone genius,

25
00:01:56,960 --> 00:02:00,560
one brilliant mind alone in a room cracking the universe,

26
00:02:00,560 --> 00:02:02,640
was always partly a myth.

27
00:02:02,640 --> 00:02:05,120
Even Einstein was not really alone.

28
00:02:05,120 --> 00:02:07,280
He was building on the work of others,

29
00:02:07,280 --> 00:02:10,560
arguing ideas with friends and his wife,

30
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:13,360
standing on a whole pile of physics that came before him.

31
00:02:14,160 --> 00:02:15,840
We just love a single hero,

32
00:02:15,840 --> 00:02:20,800
so we flatten the messy, crowded truth into one face on a poster.

33
00:02:20,800 --> 00:02:23,040
Genius has never actually been a solo act.

34
00:02:23,680 --> 00:02:25,040
We just tell the story that way.

35
00:02:25,680 --> 00:02:28,400
And here is the real reason it feels so different today.

36
00:02:29,280 --> 00:02:32,640
In 1905, the frontier of physics was close.

37
00:02:33,280 --> 00:02:37,360
Close enough that one sharp young man could sprint to the edge of human knowledge

38
00:02:37,360 --> 00:02:39,440
in his spare time and plant a flag.

39
00:02:40,160 --> 00:02:43,200
Today, that edge is incredibly far away.

40
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:46,160
To even reach the frontier of a field now,

41
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:49,040
just to get to the place where you could add something new

42
00:02:49,040 --> 00:02:50,400
takes decades of study.

43
00:02:50,960 --> 00:02:52,720
Because we know so much more than we did.

44
00:02:53,520 --> 00:02:54,960
Scientists have a name for this.

45
00:02:55,600 --> 00:02:56,880
The burden of knowledge.

46
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:02,000
Every discovery we make pushes the starting line of the next one further out.

47
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:04,160
The mountain did not get smaller.

48
00:03:04,720 --> 00:03:07,520
The hike just to reach base camp got enormous.

49
00:03:08,240 --> 00:03:10,480
So the work itself changed shape.

50
00:03:10,560 --> 00:03:13,200
The big problems left are tangled and gigantic.

51
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:15,200
Too big for any one skull to hold.

52
00:03:15,920 --> 00:03:17,840
So science became teams.

53
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:21,360
The breakthroughs are still happening constantly,

54
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:24,400
but now a single discovery might have 100 names on it.

55
00:03:24,960 --> 00:03:26,720
The Einstein of today is not missing.

56
00:03:27,280 --> 00:03:32,160
He or she is one of 200 authors on a paper you will never read,

57
00:03:32,160 --> 00:03:34,320
and you will not learn a single one of those names.

58
00:03:34,960 --> 00:03:36,480
We did not lose the geniuses.

59
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:38,960
We lost the one face to pin them on.

60
00:03:39,600 --> 00:03:42,880
Which leads to the real mystery underneath all of it.

61
00:03:42,880 --> 00:03:45,200
What even makes an Einstein in the first place?

62
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:49,040
And the honest answer from the science is that it was never just a magic brain.

63
00:03:49,600 --> 00:03:51,280
Yes, some of it is born.

64
00:03:51,280 --> 00:03:53,360
Raw intelligence is partly genetic.

65
00:03:53,920 --> 00:03:56,000
But the bigger half is conditions.

66
00:03:56,480 --> 00:03:59,360
Being in the right field at the exact right moment,

67
00:03:59,360 --> 00:04:01,040
while it is still young enough to crack.

68
00:04:01,680 --> 00:04:05,840
Having the freedom and the empty hours to just think, remember,

69
00:04:05,840 --> 00:04:09,360
Einstein had a quiet, boring job with time to daydream,

70
00:04:09,840 --> 00:04:12,640
a streak of obsession, and a great deal of luck.

71
00:04:13,280 --> 00:04:15,840
Move Einstein a hundred years in either direction,

72
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:17,840
and maybe nobody ever hears his name at all.

73
00:04:18,880 --> 00:04:20,960
So here's the quiet truth.

74
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:23,840
We did not stop producing geniuses.

75
00:04:24,640 --> 00:04:26,320
People did not get dumber.

76
00:04:26,320 --> 00:04:27,760
Two things changed.

77
00:04:27,760 --> 00:04:31,920
The shape of genius shifted from a lone hero into a hidden crowd.

78
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:37,040
And the conditions that once let a single person rewrite everything got rare.

79
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:39,360
Not because we got worse,

80
00:04:39,360 --> 00:04:42,560
but because we already know so much that no one can hold it all anymore.

81
00:04:43,120 --> 00:04:45,440
There are almost certainly people alive right now.

82
00:04:45,440 --> 00:04:47,200
Every bit as brilliant as Einstein.

83
00:04:47,760 --> 00:04:49,520
You will simply never know their names.

84
00:04:50,160 --> 00:04:52,400
They are standing in the middle of a team.

85
00:04:52,400 --> 00:04:55,440
A mile out at a frontier you cannot even see from here.

86
00:04:56,080 --> 00:04:59,680
So maybe that is the real answer to where the Einsteins went.

87
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:01,120
Nowhere.

88
00:05:01,840 --> 00:05:03,520
They are just spread out now.

89
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:09,280
The next leap that changes everything probably will not come from one lonely mind in a patent office.

90
00:05:09,280 --> 00:05:12,320
It will come from a thousand minds and a machine.

91
00:05:12,320 --> 00:05:15,120
Working on something most of us will never understand.

92
00:05:15,120 --> 00:05:17,680
And no statue will ever be built for it.

93
00:05:17,680 --> 00:05:20,080
The age of the lone genius is ending.

94
00:05:20,080 --> 00:05:21,920
Not because we ran out of geniuses.

95
00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:25,520
But because the universe got harder to surprise.

96
00:05:26,080 --> 00:05:29,760
And we finally got big enough problems that we need each other to solve them.

97
00:05:30,400 --> 00:05:34,080
So the next time you try to name a living Einstein and come up empty,

98
00:05:34,080 --> 00:05:36,400
do not read it as humanity slowing down.

99
00:05:36,960 --> 00:05:39,600
You are looking at what genius actually looks like now.

100
00:05:40,240 --> 00:05:45,840
Quieter, shared, nameless, and honestly kind of more impressive.

101
00:05:46,400 --> 00:05:49,680
There was a time when one person was enough to move the whole world.

102
00:05:49,680 --> 00:05:51,440
Now it takes all of us at once.

103
00:05:51,440 --> 00:05:53,760
And that might be the most human thing we have ever done.
